  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering prosecutions\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting requirements\n\n4. Jurisdictional Coordination\n- Cross-border investigations\n- Harmonization of legal definitions\n- Consistent enforcement approaches\n\n5. Financial Intelligence Sharing\n- International databases tracking suspicious financial activities\n- Coordinated efforts to trace and prevent money laundering networks\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- Consistent international standards for prosecuting money laundering\n- Economic sanctions against countries with weak AML frameworks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
